President Biden delivered a speech at the Major Joseph R. "Beau" Biden III National Guard/Reserve Center in New Castle, Delaware. He thanked Senator Tom Carper, Senator Chris Coons, Congresswoman Lisa Blunt Rochester, and Governor John Carney for their leadership and friendship. The President also expressed his gratitude to General Berry and General Vavala. He acknowledged the presence of Ray, a 102-year-old World War II veteran who flew 25 missions over Germany, and thanked him for his service. President Biden spoke about the sacrifices made by the men and women of the armed forces, highlighting their multiple deployments and the impact on their families. He emphasized the importance of supporting veterans and their families and mentioned the progress being made in addressing issues such as mental health, suicide prevention, and toxic exposure. The President specifically mentioned the burn pit bill and the PACT Act, which provides benefits to veterans exposed to toxic substances during their military service. He urged veterans to enroll in VA healthcare, get screened for toxic exposure, and file claims for benefits. President Biden concluded his speech by expressing his pride in the military and his commitment to fulfilling the nation's sacred obligation to care for those who serve.